In `src/app.css`, three CSS rule blocks target classes/selectors that the JavaScript never emits:
(1) The `.results-table .folder-row td { font-weight: 600; }` rule — the JS never adds a `.folder-row` class to any table row.
(2) The `.breadcrumb .separator { color: #3c3c3c; margin: 0 2px; }` rule — in `renderBreadcrumb` the JS appends a class-less `<span>textContent = '/'</span>` separator.
(3) The `.toolbar label.upload-btn { ... }` rule, its `:hover` rule, AND its descendant `.toolbar label.upload-btn input[type='file'] { display: none; }` rule — in `startApp` the JS creates `uploadLabel.className = 'btn'` (already styled by `.btn`), never `upload-btn`.

Delete those four rule blocks. Note that hiding the wrapped file input is currently done by setting `uploadInput.hidden = true` in JS, so removing the `display: none` rule is safe. Do not change any other rules. Verification: `npm test` passes (the `src/app.css.test.ts` file only asserts on `.browser-dialog` rules, which are untouched); the file builds cleanly. Spot-check that the rendered UI still shows the toolbar, breadcrumb separators, and a working hidden file input.

